Backstory: Tapeworms are super common in coastal brown bears during the salmon run. The bears get worms from feasting on raw salmon, but don’t worry - a healthy bear will hardly be bothered by the worms. Most won’t even notice they have them. Eventually the bears will pass the worms in their scat, and the eggs will wash back into the water to continue the circle of life. Earlier this fall, me and my clients arrived at our bear viewing area to see a group of photographers watching a bear. As we approached, we were treated to the unforgettable sight of an adult brown bear with a multi pronged tape worm trailing behind. It was quite the sight. And I figure since I had to witness that, you should too. Now pay it forward and tag someone who you think deserves to see this too 😂

Resharing my favorite video with a little more context this time. When I first shared this clip, I received hundreds of comments showing concern that the momma bear was much to skinny, and her and her cubs were in peril as a result. This isn’t necessarily true though. This video was taken at the start of the salmon run. The momma bear was a normal weight considering the time of year and the amount of cubs she was sustaining. As the season progressed, she put on a significant amount of weight from eating abundant salmon. However, one of the four cubs did die as a result of a conflict with another bear. The sad reality is that cubs die, a lot. The mortality rate for new cubs is high. And while cubs do die as a result of conflict with other bears, freak accidents are by far the most common cause of mortality in cubs. Drowning. Falling off cliffs. Choking on clams. The list goes on and on. I know this is sad to read, but my hope is that this knowledge helps you appreciate adult bears even more than you did before. The odds these bears must face in order to survive are beyond challenging. They deserve so much respect for all they endure to simply just be. One of the many reasons why I LOVE BEARS!!!

THE PEBBLE ROAD HAS BEEN BLOCKED!!!!! Christmas came early thanks to an Alaska Native group’s tireless fight. Through the joint efforts of Pedro Bay Corp, Bristol Bay Heritage Land Trust, the Conservation Fund, and other parters 44,000 acres of Pedro Bay Corp land are now protected from the Pebble Mine Road. This is a critically important move in protecting Bristol Bay from the devastating effects of the proposed Pebble Mine. Ivy Spohnolz said it best: “todays announcement is an affirmation of what the communities of Bristol Bay and the science have said all along: Pebble is the wrong mine in the wrong place.” The fight isn’t over yet, but I’m hopeful that the tides will keep turning against the mine. Keep your eyes and ears out for more developments!

I like elk a lot. I try not to anthropomorphize wildlife too much, but I honestly see a lot of myself in elk. Their migrations sweep across mountain tops and through valleys, mile after mile they move onward. Once they arrive to where they were going, they can’t stay very long before they have to move onward again. The main difference between me and elk though is that I can stop, take a rest, and think back on how far I’ve come. Or maybe elk do this too? I can’t say for sure. I haven’t ever asked one.

What makes the wilderness wild?   To us, it’s the mountains, the forests, the rivers, the stars, and the animals (especially the bears). 

A part of keeping the wilderness wild is being an advocate for it. We love bears, and here’s why you should too:  Bears are a keystone species. When they settle into a habitat, it’s a sign of healthy, vibrant ecosystem with plenty of food to forage and space to wander. We feel a kinship with these bears because, to us, a pantry stocked with real, nourishing food is the sign of a healthy, active life.  
We invite a piece of the wild into your home, and we hope our love of bears can inspire the wild side in you.

It's International Women's Day! I am who I am today because, in my adult life, I was lucky to meet a handful of badass women who are living the kinds of lives that I used to think were off-limits for gals. Lives full of wildness: working with wildlife, guiding wilderness expeditions, publishing fantastic images, owning their own busnisess, and basically doing everything I thought I'd never be strong, brave, or capable enough to do. But look at me now, here I am. Capable of all of the things. I know now that there is pretty much nothing that I can not do. Every time I doubt myself, I look at all of the incredible ladies I have surrounded myself with. I remember that with their support and their guidance, I can do it. 

Women of the world, you can freakin do it. Whatever your "it" may be.

Fact: When a bear is living in an ecosystem, that ecosystem thrives. But, let’s make sure you safely navigate their land and aren’t a bear’s next snack, shall we?

Tips to not becoming bear bait: 

1. Keep your distance. We promise, you can still get a good picture even if you’re a few yards away.  
2. Found yourself near a berry bush? Definitely leave that area, you’re basically at a bear’s dinner table.  
3. Stay in groups. Bears are socially awkward and don’t like to mingle — jk, but they are intimidated by big groups.  
4. Do NOT run. Plz, for the love of all things whole grain, they will proceed to chase you.

A couple seasons ago, I got to offer my time to help Idaho Fish and Game collect data on wolverines throughout the state. I had twelve data collection sites stretching across the North Eastern portion of Idaho. Each station collected DNA and trail camera photos of wolverines to contribute to a larger study by US Fish and Wildlife to determine a better estimate of wolverines populations in the lower 48. After year of data collection in multiple states, that study has finally concluded. The results enabled wolverines to be listed as threatened under the ESA. They can now be offered the protections needed to improve the survival of the few individuals we have left. During the entirety of my time working on the study, I never saw a single wolverine with my own eyes. We collected plenty of DNA in our snares and photos on our trail cams, but the actual individual wolverines eluded us. This summer in Alaska I finally saw one in the wild. She loped right behind us as we were watching a couple of subadult bears interacting in the meadow. I nearly passed out because I was so exited, hence why my photos aren’t all that great. It was such a privilege to finally see a wolverine in the wilderness after all this time! One of the best days EVER.
